\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Example of spatial mismatch between a single model grid cell and multiple census tracts within the city of San Francisco, CA. If extracting air temperature for these seven census tracts, each tract would result in the same value, despite actual microclimatic differences within these neighborhoods. Census tracts shown here are: 161.02, 202.02, 167.00, 168.01, 168.02, 162.00, 163.00, San Francisco, CA.}}{3}{figure.caption.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig-sf-tracts}{{1}{3}{Example of spatial mismatch between a single model grid cell and multiple census tracts within the city of San Francisco, CA. If extracting air temperature for these seven census tracts, each tract would result in the same value, despite actual microclimatic differences within these neighborhoods. Census tracts shown here are: 161.02, 202.02, 167.00, 168.01, 168.02, 162.00, 163.00, San Francisco, CA}{figure.caption.4}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Example of a large rural census tract in eastern Fresno County spanning Sierra Nevada foothills into higher elevation terrain, covering multiple climate model grid cells. If extracting a single representative air temperature value for this census tract, the variability of temperatures would be substantially smoothed, and may not accurately represent realistic conditions. The census tract shown here is Census Tract 64.08, Fresno County, CA.}}{4}{figure.caption.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig-rural-tract}{{2}{4}{Example of a large rural census tract in eastern Fresno County spanning Sierra Nevada foothills into higher elevation terrain, covering multiple climate model grid cells. If extracting a single representative air temperature value for this census tract, the variability of temperatures would be substantially smoothed, and may not accurately represent realistic conditions. The census tract shown here is Census Tract 64.08, Fresno County, CA}{figure.caption.6}{}}
